JOHANNESBURG – Unions are yet to sign the public sector wage agreement. Minister of Public Service and Administration Ayanda Dlodlo was not at a scheduled briefing on Monday afternoon. Her department said the majority of unions accepted government’s latest pay offer, in principle. READ: Government, unions to meet to try avert public sector strike But not all members of the bargaining council are on board with the wage proposal, with the Federation of Unions of South Africa (Fedusa) calling for more time to consult with members. The Public Servants' Association has not agreed to the three-year wage deal, while trade union federation Cosatu agreed to sign off on the deal. The agreement will see junior public sector employees getting a pay rise of seven percent, while mid-level workers will receive 6.5 percent and senior staff six percent. eNCA